Introduction to R: Data Manipulation

Filter

caption

Example: Find all the cars from Audi or Volkswagen:

filter(mpg, manufacturer %in% c("audi", "volkswagen"))

Select

  • Select groups of columns by col1:coln
  • Or select columns by calling them out by name I.E select(col1, col2, col3, col4)
  • You can deselect columns by using a negative sign. I.E. select(-col5) will select everything except col5.

Example: Select manuafacturer, model, year, cty and hwy.

select(mpg, manufacturer, model, year, cty, hwy)
select(mpg, manufacturer:hwy, -displ, -trans, -cyl, -drv)

Question: Can you explain what this most useful for in your work? Where does it fit in the spilt, apply, combine paradigm?

Arrange

What model / year of car gets the worst highway MPG?

arrange(mpg, hwy)

If I put a negative sign in front of hwy, what do you think happens?

arrange(mpg, -hwy)

Mutate

Example: Convert the MPG to KPL for both highway and city speeds.

mutate(mpg, hwy.kpl = hwy * 0.4251, hwy.cty = cty * 0.4251)

Question: How many rows did mutate give me back?

You do: Add a column to the mpg dataset with a flag for non-energy effiecent cars. Define

this as a HWY MPG below 30 mpg.

Group By / Summarise

Think of the grouping statement as the step to create a pivot table. Youre grouping the data to look at a summary value.

df <- iris
# compute the average sepal length
mean(df$Sepal.Length)
[1] 5.843333
# note: summarize gives back one row
summarize(df, mean_sepal_length=mean(Sepal.Length))
# use dplyr to group by species and compute the average and standard deviation of sepal length for each species
iris %>%
  group_by(Species) %>%
  summarize(mean_sepal_length=mean(Sepal.Length),
            sd_sepal_length=sd(Sepal.Length))

Remember This command?

# count the number of rows for each species
table(iris$Species)

    setosa versicolor  virginica 
        50         50         50

Its helpful to look at, but what if we want the same information in a dataframe so we can use it later.

# use dplyr to do the same, returning a dataframe (instead of table)
iris %>%
  group_by(Species) %>%
  summarize(num_rows=n())

Introduction to Not-a-Pipe: %>%

(Someone once told me that the %>% is called not-a-pipe since pipe was already taken, but seemingly my class are the only ones that keeps up that name.)

The pipe leads the OUTPUT of one command into the INPUT of the next one.

For example, weve seen that to filter a data frame you use

x <- filter(mpg, hwy >= 31)
newx <- mutate(x, hwy.kpl = hwy * 0.4251)

But you could also pipe in the input to the next command.

x <- mpg %>% filter(hwy >= 31) %>% mutate(hwy.kpl = hwy * 0.4251)

This makes combining output from various different functions much easier to write and read.

#Option A:
mutate(
  filter(df, Sepal.Width > 4), 
  total_width = Sepal.Width + Petal.Width)
#Option B:
df %>% 
  filter(Sepal.Width > 4) %>%
  mutate(total_width = Sepal.Width + Petal.Width)

Example data: Flights

Well use this data to practice our verbs and learn about joining!

** A little bit about the example data**

  • flights [227,496 x 14]. Every flight departing Houston in 2011.
  • weather [8,723 x 14]. Hourly weather data.
  • planes [2,853 x 9]. Plane metadata.
  • airports [3,376 x 7]. Airport metadata

Difference bettween piping and not piping.

You tell me, what is happening in this code?!

hourly_delay <- filter(
  summarise(
    group_by(
      filter(flights, !is.na(dep_delay)), 
      date, hour), 
    delay = mean(dep_delay), 
    n = n()), 
  n > 10
)
hourly_delay <- flights %>% 
  filter(!is.na(dep_delay)) %>%
  group_by(date, hour) %>%
  summarise(
    delay = mean(dep_delay),
    n = n()
  ) %>% 
  filter(n > 10)

Example: Look at the average arrival delay by city, in decreasing order. Join this with the airport information to get each destinations LAT and LONG.

Why would you do this? Maybe you want to plot cities on a map that have high delays.

delays <- flights %>%
  group_by(dest) %>%
  summarise(arr_delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE), n = n()) %>%
  arrange(-arr_delay) %>%
  inner_join(airports, by=c("dest" = "iata"))
delays

Perhaps you want to plan your next vacation by going to a state that doesnt have long delay!

delays %>% group_by(state) %>% summarise(weighted.mean(arr_delay, n))

This takes a few extra steps than needed, if we just wanted average delays by state.

How could I have looked at the same data in less lines of code?

per_hour <- flights %>%
  filter(cancelled == 0) %>%
  mutate(time = hour + minute / 60) %>%
  group_by(time) %>%
  summarise(arr_delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE), n = n())
